<subSubSection id="1CBEC0C7FFC3FFD8FF16FA51FF16F991" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="541B934CFFC3FFD8FF16FA51FF16F991" blockId="12.[151,1436,1461,2007]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="66D04F5EFFC3FFD8FF16FA51FEFAFA41" bold="true" box="[151,271,1461,1487]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Species of very small size (
<quantity id="935C3EA9FFC3FFD8FDE1FA51FD06FA41" box="[608,755,1461,1487]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="3.1" metricValueMin="2.4" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="2.75" valueMax="3.1" valueMin="2.4">2.4–3.1 mm</quantity>
), distinguished from other Iberian species of the genus by the characters in the key, mainly by the shape of hemisternites, which is a good diagnostic character in this genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1CBEC0C7FFC3FFD9FF47F9C9FDB2FE8C" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="14" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="description">
<paragraph id="541B934CFFC3FFD9FF47F9C9FDB2FE8C" blockId="12.[151,1436,1461,2007]" lastBlockId="13.[151,1436,152,538]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="14" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="66D04F5EFFC3FFD8FF47F9C9FEA2F9C9" bold="true" box="[198,343,1581,1607]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Description</emphasis>
. Dorsal vestiture composed of paler or darker ochreous scales, strongly imbricate on elytra, with metallic shimmer; setae on elytral interstriae not very dense, aligned, on dorsum elongate but moderately robust, weakly widened at apex, reclinate, semierect and more robust on declivity (rarely tear-shaped in males). Rostrum transverse, epistomal keel strong, pterygia prominent; prorostrum gibbose; frontal sulcus evident. Frons wide, with a small median fovea. Eyes normal, rounded, very prominent beyond genae, with a glabrous periocular sulcus. Antennae with very robust scape, even in first third; funicle short and robust with desmomeres 3–7 clearly transverse; club robust, elongate, evidently wider than funicle, first segment strongly cup-shaped. Pronotum with base more or less as wide as apex, transverse, scarcely sinuate at sides, disc with irregular deep punctures, covered with scales. Elytra subovoid, rather elongate, rounded at sides, weakly impressed at base, convex on dorsum, humeral calli more or less obsolete, striae with close punctures, interstriae flat, finely punctate. Legs with tibiae short and robust, protibiae on outer margin widely curved inwards before apex. Aedeagus in lateral view distinctly curved before apex, in dorsal view elliptical-elongate in apical region (
<figureCitation id="CC9F8FC9FFC2FFD9FE9BFF24FE75FF54" box="[282,384,192,218]" captionStart="FIGURES 12–13" captionStartId="58.[151,269,1961,1985]" captionTargetBox="[294,1291,206,1927]" captionTargetId="figure-50@58.[270,1317,194,1947]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURES 12–13. 12. Apex of aedeagus, dorsal view: a. Peritelus sphaeroides; b. Meira gerundana. 13. Meira medae: a. apex of aedeagus, dorsal view; b. hemisternites, dorsal view. Scale: 0.15 mm." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 12b</figureCitation>
); endophallic structures as in 
<figureCitation id="CC9F8FC9FFC2FFD9FD58FF24FCDAFF54" box="[729,815,192,218]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="55.[151,255,1999,2023]" captionTargetBox="[217,1391,189,1986]" captionTargetId="figure-36@55.[204,1394,182,1995]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="FIGURE 8. Endophallic structures: a. Peritelus sphaeroides; b. Meira gerundana; c. Meirella suturella. Scale: 0.10 mm." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 8b</figureCitation>
. Hemisternites as in 
<figureCitation id="CC9F8FC9FFC2FFD9FB9EFF24FB76FF54" box="[1055,1155,192,218]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–11" captionStartId="57.[151,269,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[198,1393,188,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-51@57.[193,1394,176,1927]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURES 10–11. 10. Hemisternites: a. Peritelus sphaeroides; b. Meira gerundana; c. Euplister hybridus. 11. Spiculum ventrale: a. Peritelus sphaeroides; b. Meira gerundana; c. Euplister hybridus. Scale: 0.15 mm." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 10b</figureCitation>
; spiculum ventrale as in 
<figureCitation id="CC9F8FC9FFC2FFD9FF16FF0CFF0FFE8C" box="[151,250,232,258]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–11" captionStartId="57.[151,269,1951,1975]" captionTargetBox="[198,1393,188,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-51@57.[193,1394,176,1927]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURES 10–11. 10. Hemisternites: a. Peritelus sphaeroides; b. Meira gerundana; c. Euplister hybridus. 11. Spiculum ventrale: a. Peritelus sphaeroides; b. Meira gerundana; c. Euplister hybridus. Scale: 0.15 mm." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 11b</figureCitation>
; spermatheca as in 
<figureCitation id="CC9F8FC9FFC2FFD9FE5FFF0CFDB1FE8C" box="[478,580,232,258]" captionStart="FIGURE 49" captionStartId="76.[151,255,1900,1924]" captionTargetBox="[243,1337,202,1872]" captionTargetId="figure-39@76.[237,1349,194,1877]" captionTargetPageId="76" captionText="FIGURE 49. Spermatheca: a. Gymnomorphus mononychus; b. Meira gerundana; c. M. medae; d. M. tarraconensis. Scale: 0.10 mm." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 49b</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1CBEC0C7FFC2FFD9FF47FEEBFE3BFEDC" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="541B934CFFC2FFD9FF47FEEBFE3BFEDC" blockId="13.[151,1436,152,538]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="66D04F5EFFC2FFD9FF47FEEBFEBEFEA7" bold="true" box="[198,331,271,297]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific name is a Latin patronymic adjective referring to the inhabitants of the province of Gerunda (now Gerona).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1CBEC0C7FFC2FFD9FF47FEBBFC3FFEF4" box="[198,970,351,378]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="541B934CFFC2FFD9FF47FEBBFC3FFEF4" blockId="13.[151,1436,152,538]" box="[198,970,351,378]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis id="66D04F5EFFC2FFD9FF47FEBBFEAAFEF7" bold="true" box="[198,351,351,377]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Distribution</emphasis>
